You need to add 2 entries to your router. One without any params and one with param supplied like this:

    $route[&#39;admin/controller/functionxyz&#39;] = &#39;admin/controller/functionxyz&#39;;
    // for only 1 param
    $route[&#39;admin/controller/functionxyz/(:any)&#39;] = &#39;admin/controller/functionxyz/$1&#39;;
    // for multiple params
    $route[&#39;admin/controller/functionxyz/(.+)&#39;] = &#39;admin/controller/functionxyz/$1&#39;;

Given a controller named `Home` in the directory */application/controllers/admin/* which has the method `public function xyz($param = null) ...` the best approach is to use remapping of the URI. But we have to **actually remap** the URI&#39;s. With that in mind, these routes should work. (Note that the `$route` key and value really do differ.)

    $route[&#39;home&#39;] = &#39;admin/home/xyz&#39;;
    $route[&#39;home/(.+)&#39;] = &#39;admin/home/xyz/$1&#39;;

So the link would be like so

    &lt;a href=&quot;example.com/home/parameter&quot;&gt; edit&lt;/a&gt;

IMO, the above is a totally unnecessary complication. Unless you&#39;re a total control freak or have hundreds of controllers there is seldom a valid reason to break CI&#39;s `/class/function/id/` URI pattern. The only outcome from putting controllers in subfolders is to make life more complicated.

